## Migration Analysis

Your code has three patterns that won't work in .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| Pattern Found | Replacement |
|---|---|
| Cancellable work loop (`while (_running)`) | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch for cleanup | `OperationCanceledException` catch |
| `Thread.ResetAbort` to continue looping | Check `IsCancellationRequested` and continue |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just continue to loop condition,
                // which will exit because token is cancelled.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive, there's nothing equivalent to Abort().
        // The thread MUST cooperate. Log a warning if it hasn't stopped.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes & Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept a token.** If it blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection<T>`), pass the token so it throws `OperationCanceledException` when cancelled:
```csharp
// Before: blocks indefinitely
var item = _queue.Take();

// After: unblocks on cancellation
var item = _queue.Take(token);
```

**2. No forced termination exists.** `Thread.Abort` has no equivalent. If `GetNextItem` calls unmodifiable code that blocks forever, your only escape hatch is to move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill`.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort` → loop continuation.** The old pattern caught the abort and reset it to keep looping. Now, if you want to continue processing after a per-item cancellation (e.g., item-level timeout), use a **linked token per item**:
```csharp
while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
    itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // per-item timeout
    try
    {
        ProcessItem(GetNextItem(token), itemCts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Item timed out, but parent isn't cancelled — rollback and continue
        RollbackCurrentTransaction();
    }
}
```

**4. `Thread.Sleep` → `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne`.** The old `Thread.Sleep(2000)` is replaced by `Thread.Join(timeout)` which is non-blocking on the caller. Inside worker code, replace sleeps with:
```csharp
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)); // wakes on cancel
```

**5. Always dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it leaks timers otherwise. Implement `IDisposable` on the host class.
